==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Leonine
<hw>Le"o*nine</hw> <pr>(l⟦emac⟧"⟦osl⟧*n⟦imac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>leoninus</ets>, fr. <ets>leo</ets>, <ets>leonis</ets>,
lion: cf. F. <ets>l⟦eacute⟧onin</ets>. See <er>Lion</er>.]</ety>
<def>Pertaining to, or characteristic of, the lion; <as>as, a
<ex>leonine</ex> look; <ex>leonine</ex> rapacity.</as></def> --
<wordforms><wf>Le"o*nine*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Leonine verse</b></col>, <cd>a kind of verse, in which
the end of the line rhymes with the middle; -- so named from
<etsep>Leo</etsep>, or <etsep>Leoninus</etsep>, a Benedictine and canon
of Paris in the twelfth century, who wrote largely in this measure,
though he was not the inventor. The following line is an
example:</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gloria <xex>factorum</xex> temere conceditur
<xex>horum</xex>.</q>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Leonotis</ent>⟦br⟧
